Why has ISIS been able to persist for so long?
New York—lethal terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad show that the reach of ISIS has extended to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and parts of Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will be able to carry out such massacres.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The issue lies in the fact that countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not treated ISIS as their main enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small combat force, with the United States estimating that it has between 20,000 and 25,000 members in Iraq and Syria, and about 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the number of active military personnel in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is nothing in comparison.
In September 2014, President Obama of the United States pledged to "eradicate ISIS," but the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), have consistently focused on toppling President Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
Recently, Major General Herzi Halevy of the Israeli Army spoke bluntly (as relayed to me by a journalist present at the speech): "Israel does not want to see the Syrian situation end with ISIS being defeated, the superpowers withdrawing from the region, and Israel facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two main quasi-military adversaries—Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the United States, the Syria war is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by Secretary of Defense Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told General Wesley Clark of the United States:
But we (did learn from the Gulf War) that we could use force in the region — — in the Middle East — — and the Soviets would not stop us.
Before the emergence of the next superpower challenges us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regime — — Syria, Iran (as written), Iraq.
The multiple wars the United States has fought in the Middle East — — Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. — — were to get the Soviet Union and later Russia out of the competition, allowing the United States to establish its hegemony alone.
These "efforts" were a complete failure.
For Saudi Arabia and Israel, the main objective is to topple Assad in order to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a large-scale proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which has been fought in Syria and Yemen, and is also intensifying along the frontlines of Shia-Sunni confrontation in Bahrain and other countries in the region with separatist tendencies, including Saudi Arabia itself.
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional position.
But Turkey now faces three adversaries along its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But ISIS-sponsored terrorist attacks in Turkey may change this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for quasi-military operations.
But both countries have expressed willingness to cooperate with the United States in combating ISIS and can also cooperate on resolving other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent, as its focus has been on toppling Assad.
The U.S. foreign policy community condemns Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia condemns the United States for attempting to topple Assad.
These complaints appear to be directly opposing, but in reality, they are not.
The United States and its allies' attempts to topple Assad violate the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense as stipulated in the Charter.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
ISIS's persistent existence highlights three major strategic flaws in U.S. foreign policy and a fatal tactical flaw.
First, the neoconservative demand to achieve American hegemony through regime change is not only ignorant of the bloody mindset; it is also the classic imperialist overreach.
Every attempt by the United States to do so has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the Director of Central Intelligence has long supported Sunni jihadists through secret operations funded by Saudi Arabia.
Conversely, these jihadists gave rise to ISIS, which was a direct (perhaps unintended) consequence of the policy pursued by the Central Intelligence Agency and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, the United States' characterization of Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies is largely a self-fulfilling outdated prophecy.
Rebuilding relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, tactically, the United States' attempt to wage a dual front war against Assad and ISIS has already failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the Nusayri Front (al-Nusira Front), will fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistics support, Assad and his Iraqi allies could defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to hold power; indeed, Russia will remain an ally of Syria; indeed, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for some time still under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome would not only eradicate ISIS on the Middle Eastern soil but also lay the foundation for a more comprehensive缓解 of regional tensions.
The United States and Russia can begin to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
(NATO's commitment to not admitting Ukraine into the alliance or escalating ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits.
Adopting a cooperative approach to combat ISIS would provide Saudi Arabia and Turkey with justification and opportunity to seek new pragmatic arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by enabling Iran to build cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with the West, thereby increasing the chances of a delayed Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the current strategic flaws of the West — particularly the United States.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The issue lies in whether the United States will conduct the strategic reassessment necessary to achieve this goal.
